## 1. üéØ Core Website Design Principles

### 1.1. Clear Purpose and Goal
- **Single primary objective**: Each website should have one clear primary goal (lead generation, product sales, information delivery, portfolio showcase)
- **User-focused messaging**: Content should immediately communicate value proposition to target audience
- **Conversion-oriented**: Design should guide users toward desired actions
- **Content hierarchy**: Most important information should be most prominent

### 1.2. Content Organization and Structure
- **Logical flow**: Content should follow natural reading and scanning patterns (F-pattern, Z-pattern)
- **Distinct sections**: Use visual separators (background colors, spacing, imagery) to create clear content blocks
- **Progressive disclosure**: Show essential information first, reveal details on demand (especially important for one-page sites)
- **Scannable content**: Break text into digestible chunks with headings, lists, and visual elements

### 1.3. Navigation and Wayfinding
- **Clear navigation structure**: Users should understand where they are and how to navigate
- **Anchor-based navigation**: For one-page sites, use smooth scroll anchors with sticky navigation
- **Breadcrumbs**: For multi-page sites, show current location in navigation hierarchy

### 1.4. Visual Storytelling
- **Compelling hero section**: First impression matters‚Äîuse strong visuals and clear value proposition
- **Visual hierarchy**: Guide attention through size, color, contrast, and placement
- **Consistent branding**: Maintain visual identity throughout all sections
- **Balanced media**: Use images, illustrations, and video purposefully without sacrificing performance

### 1.5. Performance and Optimization
- **Fast loading**: Prioritize quick initial load times for better user experience
- **Performance-first mindset**: Consider performance impact of all design decisions
- **Core Web Vitals**: Optimize for LCP (Largest Contentful Paint), FID (First Input Delay), CLS (Cumulative Layout Shift)

## 2. ‚úÖ DO (Recommended Practices)

### 2.1. Website Structure

#### One-Page Website Structure
- ‚úÖ **Hero section with clear value proposition**: Immediately communicate what you offer
- ‚úÖ **Distinct content blocks**: Organize into logical sections (Features, About, Testimonials, Contact)
- ‚úÖ **Sticky navigation with anchor links**: Help users jump to sections without losing context
- ‚úÖ **Multiple strategic CTAs**: Place primary call-to-action in hero, mid-scroll, and footer
- ‚úÖ **Visual section separators**: Use background colors, spacing, or imagery to distinguish sections

```html
<!-- ‚úÖ Good: One-page website structure with clear sections -->
<nav>
  <a href="#hero">Home</a>
  <a href="#features">Features</a>
  <a href="#about">About</a>
  <a href="#contact">Contact</a>
</nav>

<section id="hero">
  <h1>Clear Value Proposition</h1>
  <p>Supporting message</p>
  <a href="#contact">Get Started</a>
</section>

<section id="features">
  <h2>Features</h2>
</section>

<section id="contact">
  <h2>Ready to Get Started?</h2>
  <a href="#contact-form">Contact Us</a>
</section>
```

#### Multi-Page Website Structure
- ‚úÖ **Clear site hierarchy**: Organize pages into logical categories
- ‚úÖ **Consistent navigation**: Maintain same navigation structure across all pages
- ‚úÖ **Breadcrumbs**: Show current location in deep navigation structures
- ‚úÖ **Footer navigation**: Include important links in footer for easy access
- ‚úÖ **Homepage as hub**: Homepage should clearly guide users to relevant sections

### 2.2. Content Organization

- ‚úÖ **Headline hierarchy**: Use proper H1-H6 structure (one H1 per page)
- ‚úÖ **Section IDs for anchors**: Use semantic IDs for anchor navigation
- ‚úÖ **Meaningful section names**: Each section should have clear purpose
- ‚úÖ **Content blocks**: Group related content together with consistent spacing
- ‚úÖ **Visual breaks**: Use whitespace, colors, or imagery to separate sections

> **Reference**: See [HTML Best Practices](../../html/html.mdc) for semantic HTML structure and heading hierarchy details.

### 2.3. Call-to-Action (CTA) Strategy

- ‚úÖ **Primary CTA prominence**: Make primary action visually stand out
- ‚úÖ **Multiple CTA placements**: Place CTAs at key decision points (hero, after features, footer)
- ‚úÖ **Clear action language**: Use specific, benefit-focused copy ("Start Free Trial" vs "Click Here")
- ‚úÖ **Contrasting colors**: Use contrasting colors to make CTAs stand out
- ‚úÖ **Consistent CTA design**: Use same style for primary CTAs throughout site

```html
<!-- ‚úÖ Good: Clear CTA with benefit-focused copy -->
<section>
  <h1>Transform Your Workflow</h1>
  <p>Join thousands of teams already using our platform</p>
  <a href="/signup">Start Free Trial</a>
  <p>No credit card required</p>
</section>
```

